29 The Commission contends that the Tribunal's reasons for decision contain two errors of law and therefore, on appeal, raise two questions of law:


 (1) the proper construction of ss 120 , 120A (3) and 120A (4) of the VE Act and, in particular, the meaning of the phrase " kind of death " in s 120A(4) of the VE Act;
 (2) even if the Tribunal had properly construed ss 120 , 120A (3) and 120A (4) of the VE Act and, in particular, the meaning of the phrase " kind of death " in s 120A(4) of the VE Act in finding that the kind of death met by the veteran was " death by road accident ", whether the Tribunal erred in failing to determine the application of pension by applying the reasoning of Goldberg J in Repatriation Commission v McKenna (1998) 28 AAR 7 at 15-16 which was endorsed by the Full Court in McKenna v Repatriation Commission [1999] FCA 323 ; (1999) 86 FCR 144 at [20] . (I will describe this as the " McKenna principle").
